### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

service-worker

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

I was on Angular 16 and the service worker worked with no issue. It worked exactly as described in the server-side docs:


> If you are using Angular on the server in combination with the Angular service worker, the behavior deviates from the normal server-side rendering behavior. The initial server request will be rendered on the server as expected. However, after that initial request, subsequent requests are handled by the service worker and always client-side rendered.

After the upgrade to Angular 17, this has stopped working. My requests are always bypassing the service-worker cache and retrieve the resources from the server.

I am using a basic setup.

Here is the content of `ngsw-config.json`:

```JSON
{
  "$schema": "./node_modules/@angular/service-worker/config/schema.json",
  "index": "/index.html",
  "assetGroups": [
    {
      "name": "app",
      "installMode": "prefetch",
      "resources": {
        "files": [
          "/favicon.ico",
          "/index.html",
          "/manifest.webmanifest",
          "/*.css",
          "/*.js"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "assets",
      "installMode": "lazy",
      "updateMode": "prefetch",
      "resources": {
        "files": [
          "/assets/**",
          "/*.(svg|cur|jpg|jpeg|png|apng|webp|avif|gif|otf|ttf|woff|woff2)"
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "dataGroups": [
    {
      "name": "translations",
      "urls": [
        "api/translation/i18n/**"
      ],
      "cacheConfig": {
        "strategy": "performance",
        "maxAge": "15m",
        "maxSize": 50
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

I have debugged `ngsw-worker.js` and found out that inside the `assignVersion(event)` we have this part of the code that returns null after the update to Angular 17.

```
if (this.state !== DriverReadyState.NORMAL) {
   return null;
}
```

This is caused by the fact that the state value in my case is  `DriverReadyState.EXISTING_CLIENTS_ONLY`.

So the next question was why? With a longer debug found that the state is set like this inside the `async versionFailed(appVersion, err)` method with the following error

```
Error: Hash mismatch (cacheBustedFetchFromNetwork): dummy/manifest.webmanifest: expected 28e5100762138d95be65b2e1ab570f2055dc0ade, got 61f2946b132d6d0633a3ab5eaba61cc869bae4bf (after cache busting)
    at PrefetchAssetGroup.cacheBustedFetchFromNetwork (dummy/ngsw-worker.js:479:21)
    at async PrefetchAssetGroup.fetchFromNetwork (dummy/ngsw-worker.js:454:19)
    at async PrefetchAssetGroup.fetchAndCacheOnce (dummy/ngsw-worker.js:433:21)
    at async dummy/ngsw-worker.js:538:9
    at async dummy/ngsw-worker.js:524:9
```

